      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "Interpretation:\n- The very large K1 for Hg²⁺–glutathione (log K ≈ 26) and the high value for Hg²⁺–cysteine (log K ≈ 14.4) indicate exceptionally strong Hg–S bonding. These thiolate donors outperform representative N‑donor (ethylenediamine, log K ≈ 14.3) and O‑donor (hydroxide, log K ≈ 10.6) ligands under similar conditions.\n- Although ethylenediamine binds Hg²⁺ strongly (chelate effect), thiolates—especially biological thiols like glutathione—are typically stronger, consistent with HSAB expectations (Hg²⁺ is a soft Lewis acid preferring soft S donors).\n- Practically, this strong Hg–S affinity underlies the high sequestration of Hg²⁺ by protein cysteine residues and the efficacy of thiol-based chelators; O‑donors are generally weaker competitors at comparable pH/ionic strength.",
